article.description: Tamika Catchings had 19 points, 13 rebounds and a blocked shot in the final seconds to lead the Indiana Fever past the Phoenix Mercury 61-60 Saturday night.
article.headline: Catchings key as Indiana holds on
article.linkText: Mercury drop the ball late as Fever 'Catch' a break
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tamika Catchings came up with the big plays
at both ends of the court and timely free throws in the final
minute for the Indiana Fever.

Catchings scored 19 points, 13 rebounds and had three of her
team's nine blocked shots as the Fever (9-7) beat the Phoenix
Mercury 61-60 Saturday night without making a field goal in the
final 9:06.

It was Catchings' second double-double of the season, moving her
into a tie with Lauren Jackson for 10th place on the WNBA's career
list with 24.

The game included 17 ties and seven lead changes. The final
switch came when Catchings, who has made 23 consecutive free throws
in her last three games, hit a pair from the line with 36.6 seconds
to play.

"Great players step up and make plays," said Indiana coach
Brian Winters.

Indiana came up with 15 turnovers and turned them into 13
points.

"In the second half, we picked up our defense, turnovers hurt
us," Mercury coach Carrie Graf said.

Phoenix got the ball to rookie Diana Taurasi underneath to try
the go-ahead basket, but the shot was blocked by Catchings with
11.9 seconds to go. The ball bounced out of bounds, but Phoenix
maintained possession with 11.3 seconds to go.

"In the last five minutes, I'll do what I have to do to get the
team a win. If I have to guard her for us to win, that's what I
needed to do," Catchings said. "After watching film on her, I knew
she would either step back and shoot a 3 or get into someone's
body when she shot. I am a little longer than she is and was able
to block the shot."

After a timeout, Taurasi had another shot attempt blocked by
Kristen Rasmussen and the Mercury again retained possession with
4.8 seconds to go.

Phoenix botched its final chance to tie by committing its 15th
turnover of the game with 2.3 seconds left.

Ann DeForge led Phoenix with 18 points and Taurasi had 14.
Taurasi, who came into the game fourth in the league in scoring
with an 18.5 average, was 4 of 13 from the field and missed all
five of her 3-point attempts.

"Defensively I thought we did some good things. However, in the
end it was just not our night," Taurasi said.

Reserve Kelly Schumacher had 11 for Indiana and Deana Jackson
contributed 10. The Indiana reserves outscored Phoenix's subs 17-2.

Phoenix was outrebounded 38-28 and the Fever had an 18-7
advantage on the offensive glass with Catchings matching her
career-high of nine.

"If you can't rebound, you can't win," Taurasi said.
